<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871202-0098 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:Blown Away</HL><DD> 12/02/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG) </IN><TEXT>   In 1980, the federal government's Energy Department lavished $55 million and Bonneville Power chipped in $5 million to build three giant windmills to generate electricity in Washington state. What was supposed to be a &quot;multimegawatt wind farm&quot; turned out to be so much hot air. The windmills were grossly inefficient, and kept falling apart to boot. A private firm has now bought them at auction for scrap, paying $28,000. The infatuation with &quot;alternative energy sources&quot; turns out to be very expensive tilting at windmills indeed. </TEXT></DOC>